Virtusa interview questions - tech lead position 

1. difference between deployement and replicaset and daoemonset and statefulset (what key words you will be writing over the, 
for ex : deployement.yml – rolling update, canary)

Ans. Deployment - Creates and manages ReplicaSets
                  Supports rolling updates & rollbacks
                  Ensures the desired number of Pods are running
ReplicaSet:
           A ReplicaSet ensures a specific number of Pod replicas are running at all times.
           What it does
               Keeps Pods running (recreates them if they crash)
                No deployment strategy (no rolling updates by itself)
DaemonSet
      What it is:
      A DaemonSet ensures one Pod runs on every node (or selected nodes).
      What it does
     Automatically adds Pods when new nodes join
      Removes Pods when nodes are removed

what is chart.yml file contains in K8

Ans. Chart.yaml describes what the Helm chart is, its version, and basic info so Helm knows how to install and manage it.
mychart/
 ├── Chart.yaml
 ├── values.yaml
 └── templates/

what files will be present in helm chart ?

Ans. Helm Chart Structure
     mychart/
├── Chart.yaml
├── values.yaml
├── charts/
├── templates/
│   ├── deployment.yaml
│   ├── service.yaml
│   ├── ingress.yaml
│   ├── _helpers.tpl
│   └── NOTES.txt
├── .helmignore

what you will declare in values.yml etc
 Ans. Application & Deployment Settings
      Service Configuration
      Ingress Configuration

what is node affinity and pod affinity  in K8 ?

Ans. Node Affinity:
     Node affinity lets you tell Kubernetes which nodes a Pod can or should run on, based on node labels.

    Pod Affinity:
    Pod affinity controls scheduling based on other Pods’ labels.

Node vs Pod Affinity (Comparison)
Based on	Node labels	Pod labels

